There are many reasons for the fires. One being, we need to let our forest fires burn. When we don't allow forest fires to happen, organic material builds up on the forest and when it eventually does burn, it burns so hotly that it ends up destroying the topsoil and the trees. These trees in California have evolved to withstand certain temperatures of forest fires but these current fires are burning much hotter than ever and this destroys trees that have historically withstood the heat. Also in California, the winds are very powerful and allow the fires plenty of fuel to spread very rapidly. Finally, climate change has also played a part in increasing the severity of the fires. The heat has created more dry material that acts as kindling for the flames.  If we want to stop the fires: 1) Let more forest fires burn 2) clear excessive dry brush 3) reduce our carbon footprint.

The forest floor, also called detritus, duff and the O horizon, is one of the most distinctive features of a forest ecosystem. It mainly consists of shed vegetative parts, such as leaves, branches, bark, and stems, existing in various stages of decomposition above the soil surface. Although principally composed of non-living organic material, the forest floor also teems with a wide variety of fauna and flora. It is one of the richest components of the ecosystem from the standpoint of biodiversity because of the large number of decomposers[1] and predators present, mostly belonging to invertebrates, fungi, algae, bacteria, and archaea. Certain (adapted) plants may be more apparent in tropical forests, where rates of metabolism and species diversity are much higher than in colder climates. Source: Wikipedia (& D. I'm a bush firefighter. Yes, we actually DO rake things, during a fire. It's a highly technical process, called "making a fire break". We use a special rake, called a Rake-hoe, or Rako, designed over 100 years ago and still made and sold today. We scrape away all the fuel, back to bare "mineral earth" in a strip 1-2 metres wide, so that the fire will stop at the edge. Often this is done before we actually LIGHT A NEW FIRE to back-burn the fuel, thus containing the fire inside a burned zone. So Orange Moron DID see firefighters "raking the forest floor" LOL. But he has literally NO FUCKING IDEA as to why.

@Teemu I live in Norway and am involved in somewhat larger forestry in the Netherlands. Here in Norway, they do not rake the forest floor, rather they try and make people aware of forest fire danger every summer. It is very difficult getting into the forest with large machines, which is why certain clean up projects only can be combined with regular forestry. What is used for forestry nowadays are so called Harvesters, that both cut the trees, removes the branches, and puts the logs on a trailer. However you have to create pathways for these machines. Usually they do this by taking the branches from the trees and the forest floor and place them in front of the machine. In this manner there is less compression of the earth underneath. The weight of these machines would otherwise compress the earth so much that it greatly reduces fertility (which is why our industrial agriculture has caused such a dramatic drop in soil fertility). Also, you can treat the forest floor with a kind of plow afterwards, in order to create a better growing bed for seedlings. So, in conclusion, the removal of (dead) material from the forest floor (not the 'floor of the forest'), is usually combined with the logging prospects. Otherwise it's too difficult to get into the forest, and let's not mention what the costs would be for this kind of clean up. The forests around California probably have different management that does not always coincide with industrial forestry. Plus that the resources to remove dead material through manual labor simply aren't there. There is a way to effectively remove dead plant material from the forest floor, which is through burning the vegetation in same manner as the Aboriginals in Australia do in certain parts of the country. This does pose some benefits, but also contains many disadvantages. Which is the reason why it has been prohibited in so many countries in Europe, since we used to have similar practices.

Didn't your grandfather ever tell you about the great raking of Vammalla 1967? Well, allow me to teach you a valuable lesson in history.  The year prior Finland had come up a bit short on the war reparations paid at the time for the Soviet Union, so in the early spring Chairman Malenkov had made a ruthless demand for the Finns to supply them with massive amounts of gardening tools to make up for the difference. The demand was under a great threat of economic sanctions, which would have halted the vodka importation for an unknown period of time, which was obviously unacceptable for the Finns. Hesitantly the whole nation complied, still recovering from the war at the time, unable to afford any shortage of the precious liquor favored by so many. After all, this was two years before the legislation regarding the sale of standard beer in grocery stores (462/1968) had passed, and proper drinks for Saturday sauna were not as easy to come by as they are today. However, come autumn, come the leaves, and the forests would be filled with the decaying fire hazards the great nation of Finland had tended and cleared out so carefully throughout the centuries with the ancient art of forest raking. The situation was looking very dire, and as the summer was closing to the end, the leaders of the country were desperately searching for a viable solution. But behold, for the great innovation of the nation strikes again. Unknown to the government at the time, the engineers of Fiskars corporation had also foreseen the upcoming travesty and worked hard throughout the summer and had finally come up with a plan just in time to save the nation from nature's garbage. The corporation had started mass-production of scissors almost as soon as the Soviet demand had been fulfilled. It took way less time and resources to produce these scissors than new rakes would have cost, and it was possible to spread them across the country way more conveniently in smaller packages, and to top it all, technically they needed not be categorized as gardening tools, preventing Soviet claim over them. The young nation had been blessed with new hope for a salvation indeed. The scissors were also equipped with orange handles in order to make them easier to locate if lost in the forest, and it was this design that remains iconic to this very day! That is indeed what Fiskars is still the best known for; The orange-handled scissors of 1967! When the autumn closed in and the leaves started to turn the reddish and orange hue, the nation got to work. For the following weeks the Finns cut the leaves down using the scissors and collected them into garbage bags before they could fall down and pollute to great forest floors. And this is how the nation was saved once again!  To this very day the Finns rake the floors of the forests in order to keep their nation safe and sound from the great threats of the nature. The end.

Â @pataplanÂ  But Seth is ridiculing him for his choice of word which is in fact the correct word for describing the ground in a forest. We would cut our fire breaks a few months before the dry season then rake/clear them of flammable material by burning the breaks a month before dry season. The key was to burn the breaks after the material we cut down had time to dry but not when the woods were already too dry. Most fires you have to deal with are when people burning their breaks lose control of the fire but you never burn them when it's windy and the canopies of the surrounding trees are not dry enough to catch a light.  If you just rake/clear your breaks then you have to monitor the breaks because the fire can still cross the break albeit at a much slower rate. If you cut then burn the breaks then you can forget about them, no fire will not cross via the ground We would keep in touch in the dry season and if I fire was spotted we would work out the direction it would go and the wind conditions. If it was windy we would rush out with chainsaws and increase the size of the breaks in the direction the fire was heading and then spray water onto the canopy of the trees on the opposite side of the break from the fire. Only one rule in fighting and preventing wild fires, remove the flammable material. No heroics are required you cannot fight a wild fire, you cannot even get close enough to attack it with water hoses. You get ahead of it and cut breaks, it's not rocket science if the whole community gets involved you can stop any wild fire. Alexandra Mac, you are correct. One of the most important elements in Forestry Fire Fighting is creating fire breaks, like you described. This is done by hand, and with machinery. The objective is to separate leading ground to discourage or minimize the continuity of the fire/flames, as well as keeping access roads open, and for creating on-the-spot temporary shelters for the firefighters if the flames are catching up to them too fast. It is a constant process, extremely laborious and physically demanding. The methods of Forestry Firefighting are much different than for structural/city/town firefighting. The preventive "raking" of "the floor" that the President speaks of is a misinterpretation on his part. Removing flammable debris from the ground is not a year-round preventive clean up, like removing the grease from a kitchen hood or something like that. "Raking" (not usually done with a rake) is part of cutting off the path of the fires, once it is known where they are tending to go to, in an effort of staying ahead of them. Sometimes this works, sometimes the fire overcomes even the cross paths that were previously treated.

There are fire smart programs that reduce the amount of ground litter (dry dead organic matter) in the urban forest interface and also include making sure there aren't trees with 10 metres of structures. Obviously these programs are meant to be for only near urban areas and not the entire forest, but by reducing the amount of fuel you create a fire break in these urban forest interface areas which can reduce the severity. Actually, "the forest floor" is a more specific term that denotes an important part of the ecosystem which constitutes what we call a forest. It is the part of decomposing organic matter that establishes after "the forest" (the sum of trees) has been established.  Such as leafs, etc. which form a layer on the ground. Taking care of the forest floor in such a way as to not disturb the eco system beyond necessity and yet minimize fire hazard is rather important. If too much is left for decomposition in an area that gets very dry during summertime (or in other ways is susceptible to wildfires), it can act like an "ignition / fuel mat" by which fire spreads far more rapidly than by, say, from tree to tree. Hence becoming much harder to contain within as short a time frame as possible. Further, the denser a forest floor that catches fire, the greater the probability of extensive root fire. Which should be avoided.  I'm not a huge Trump fan, but give due where it is. Taking care of forest floors is important people. Here in scandinavia forest management is a five year university education. Not that people go around with rakes like 1600 century farmers, nor that inattention to forest floors should be solely blamed for an increase in wildfires. Manbearpig is real and stuff.

Trump is an idiot but, to be fair, it is the "forest floor" not the "forest ground" just like it's called a "canopy" not the "ceiling"; your East-coast elitism is showing.  Watch a Planet Earth episode.  Also, raking undergrowth prevents a ground fire from involving the tree trunks and canopy and canopy fires are what are spread so fast that people can't escape.  Make fun of how dumb he sounds (and saying the President of Finland told him about raking was pretty dumb sounding) all you want but he's not wrong.  California's fire problem does stem from a lack of management stretching back to the 50's.  One controlled burn got out of hand so they abandoned the practice, now they have 60 years of fuel and the climate is only getting drier and the problem is only getting worse; compound that with communities expanding right up to the edge of ecosystems where fire is a natural part of the cycle and you get large scale property damage.  I feel for the victims of these fires, I really do but the fires are the predictable result of a chain of events.  Laughing at Trump's remarks (while usually justified) overlooks the fact that the answer isn't to stop climate change (though, that's not a bad idea) it's to live in harmony with our ecosystem in general and understand environmental risk. The US doesn't really import that much oil from Saudi Arabia. As of 2015, the US produces 76% of the petroleum they consume (petroleum is a broader category that includes crude oil, refined oil products such as diesel, biofuels etc.). The US actually exports more petroleum than we (I'm from the US) import. And the majority of what the US does import comes from Canada, not Saudi Arabia.  Saudi Arabia matters to the US for a few reasons. When it comes to oil, it doesn't matter who "gives" the US oil - if Saudi Arabia starts exporting less oil, it will raise the price of our oil regardless of how much we buy from Saudi Arabia. The US doesn't buy Iranian oil when the sanctions are in place, but still, Iranian oil production affects our price of oil - because when Iran produces less, Asian countries (which still relied on Iran's oil) need to buy more from countries the US buys from, so there is less for everyone, so the price rises. That's how international economics works.  But I suspect the US tries to stay friendly with Saudi Arabia more because of military reasons than economic ones. This is grossly oversimplified, but Saudi Arabia is against Iran, Iran is against Israel, we're friends with Israel, and the enemy of my enemy is my friend. Saudi Arabia also helps us out in some ways when it comes to maneuvering with Iraq and Afghanistan, although they also seem to be helping our enemies as well. It's very complicated, and I'm not pretending to get all of it. But I think the focus on oil is a bit of a red herring at the moment. Stability in the oil markets is always nice, but I don't think it's the US's major priority at the moment.

Trump doesn't seem to understand that Finland sits in the subarctic and hemiboreal zone, with boreal forests, ranging from maritime to continental climate due to the warm Gluf Stream and moderating effects of the Baltic Sea, with cold winters and comparatively warm summers for its latitude (compared with Alaska, Siberia or Greenland).  While California has a Mediterranean climate, with arid deserts to temperate rainforests and mountain ranges, but has been suffering from heat and massive droughts for years now, made worse by a lowering of the water table due to massive water consumption from agriculture and cities and digging of ever more wells. California's forests are adapted to regular small wildfires; the decade-long obsession of preventing the smaller fires, as well as increased growth of grass due to changing rain patterns in recent years, has let to flammable underbrush piling up resulting in huge fires that kill the trees. Climate change is real; it doesn't magically start fires, but it increases temperature extremes and changes air and rain patterns. But constantly "raking" the forests so that they look "tidy" would also be a bad idea ecologically, as animals and young plants are dependant on the cover and nutrients provided by slow rotting dead leaves and similar.  North American soils originally knew no earthworms, so flora and fauna adapted to slow recycling of lead litter by bacteria and fungi... all earthworms they have now are invasive species brought over from Europe over the past centuries.

I am starting to wonder if Trump has Wernickeâ€“Korsakoff syndrome. Korsakoff syndrome, a neurological disorder with neuronal loss, caused by a lack of thiamine (vitamin B1) in the brain, which can be the result of chronic alcoholism, thiamine deficiency from dietary deficiencies, mercury poisoning, dialysis, chemotherapy, or just old age. One of the typical symptoms is "confabulation" (false memories): the patient will invent false stories about events that never happened and then become convinced they are true. Other symptoms include lack of insight, disinterest in new things (apathy), euphoria, fixation amnesia (loss of immediate memory, being unable to remember events of the past few minutes), blackouts, false recognition of places, mental excitation, and in severe cases anterograde or retrograde amnesia. Which is why Korsakoff syndrome (also spelled Korsakow syndrome) is called _amnestic-confabulatory syndrome_.  Korsakoff syndrome often comes coupled with Wernicke encephalopathy: damage to the Wernicke area in the brain's temporal lobe region, an area involved in the comprehension or understanding of written and spoken language. Wernicke encephalopathy is characterized by the presence of changes in mental states (confusion), unsteady stance and gait (ataxia) due to lack of coordination of muscle movements which can also lead to slurred speech, and a weakness or paralysis of the extraocular muscles of the eye (ophthalmoplegia) resulting in odd or slow eye movements.  Wernicke encephalopathy is also called receptive aphasia; patients demonstrate fluent speech output but have difficulty understanding the content of written text and spoken language. Therefore, they may produce a large amount of speech without much meaning, and are not aware of their errors they are making while speaking. Their writing often reflects speech in that it tends to lack content or meaning.  Those are all symptoms that fit what we have seen from Trump: Confabulation, inability to concentrate, confusion, unsteady gait (ataxia), slurred speech, rambling nonsensical speeches and tweets (aphasia), sudden emotional outbursts, disinterest in learning new things, lack of insight. And how much of his protestations, when caught in a lie, of "I never said that!" are conmanship and how much is caused by amnesia or dementia, we can't say for certain.

It's summer here now, so totally wrong season for it, but with climate change, it's a nightmare to try to do even in winter, so we do it whenever possible, meaning even now some is actually happening. Here's a map of current bushfires in Sydney https://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/fire-information/fires-near-me  7 bushfires,  1 grassfire  4 hazard reduction fires (deliberately lit controlled burns)  That site btw is always active & being updated, anytime we smell smoke/can't see out our door cause it's so thick, we can go there & see exactly what's going on in our area & if we need to think about evacuating. Once it reaches "emergency warning" sms's are sent to all mobile phones in the effected area advising of the fire, if evacuation is recommended/mandatory & where evacuation centres are located (it's very rare we have mandatory evacuations for fit healthy people who are prepared to fight the fire in well prepared homes, but for everyone else, they are highly recommended in many settings & centres set up to encourage compliance - not that you need prompting with the level of smoke & automatic fear that goes with that!) It's not just debris on the forest floor. there are critters, bugs, rodents of all stripes making a living in the humus. Maybe he will learn the difference between forest Management and landscaping. If he were to say we should create fire perimeters around our towns, villages and outposts. Removing dead stand trees and fallen trees, thinning thickets, removing low hanging dead branches from mature trees. clearing woody material that can fuel fires to make a buffer perimeter to provide a cushion to escape an approaching fire then that would make sense and that is what we already do. Raking is not a very important part of fire prevention. Things above ground level burn better. A management plan doesn't stop the fire threat. The purpose is to slow the advancing fire enough to widen the window people have to escape. the Camp fire was anomalous with hurricane force winds driving an electrically sparked fire no management could slow or mitigate the event. It would be far cheaper to convert all remote locations to solar and remove all above ground high voltage feeder lines than to have 1 mile perimeters raked around all our forest communities. trumps comments and suggestions are insulting to forest managers deeply steeped in a fire management crisis caused by a changing climate that trump says is a hoax.

Raking the leaves ... 9:08  step back for a minute and realize what every media outlet is missing: the firefighters were creating a firebreak with a tool called a McLeod (not a rake). In optimum conditions, a bulldozer will clear the majority of brush, firefighters then clean up any flammable "debris", then "fight fire with fire" (Sometimes, a bulldozer is not available and the firebreak must be created completely by hand). Depending on a number of conditions (wind speed, wind direction, etc.) the firebreak can be made several hundred yards ahead of the oncoming fire line. After the firebreak is created, firefighters ignite that brush/debris with flares and let it burn back towards the approaching fire line while standing guard with hoses to ensure that the fire they created doesn't jump across the firebreak and spread further. This allows the fire to burn out in a controlled area which is then "mopped up" for hot spots. Fighting fire with fire this way is an effective technique that has been used for decades. It is stupid to try to "chase" an out-of-control fire; it is best to advance in front of it, create a firebreak, and burn the foliage in a controlled way to the fire line. Once it's burned, there's nothing left to burn.  ... the media should stop chasing after these Trumpian out-of-control fires of stupidity and start to be more pro-active about the extreme dangerousness of this orange buffoon with malignant narcissistic personality disorder because he is an absolute threat to our national security ...

tl;dr The POTUS has the RAM of a mechanical calculator.  Afforestation or forestation (which Trump apparently heard correctly) is the practice of planning wooded areas with specific species being planted strategically in order to define areas where potential fires are less prone to spread too quickly. Apparently what the President of Finland was talking about was how they draw a plan to make their forests less likely to feed a wildfire, by using the characteristics of certain trees which are not as combustible as others, to define borders within the forests themselves.  For example, the fact that much of California has seen an increase in numbers of eucalyptus trees in the last century makes it a high risk area for wildfires. Eucalyptus trees soak up a lot of the water in the soil, their sap is highly flammable and they grow incredibly fast, covering wide areas which end up with no botanical diversity. This means that any area where you have nothing but eucalyptus trees is going to burn almost uncontrollably. With trees growing too close to the roads any fire can cross them with just a little bit of wind, and the fire fighters have a harder time finding viable paths to fence the flames.  For contrast, the massive redwoods have evolved to grow their bark in a way that makes them less liable to burn (almost like asbestos). They also contain no resin or pitch, so they have virtually no fuel to feed a fire, compared to pine or eucalyptus trees. Sadly, trees with these characteristics are disappearing and being replaced by more economically viable species. There's also the issue of cleaning up the forests, which is basically something people used to do when they collected firewood, and no longer do in modern times, leaving the forest floors covered in dry material that adds to the problem. As for climate change, yes, it's relevant. Higher temperatures in later years have dried out the vegetation faster and in larger quantities, and rain is coming later, so there's no humidity to help prevent the potential for fires and a lot of stuff that's bone dry and just waiting to burn. So Trump heard the words, recorded some random ones and failed to understand cleaning a forest isn't done like his gardeners at Mar-a-Lago clean the golf courses. Surprisingly, raking is a technique which was and is still used to keep the underbrush in check. Yes, the rakes are vastly different. They are attachments to those giant machines they use to cut the trees down. The idea is to "clean" the forest with these "rakes" so that there is next to no flammable material between the trees left standing (i.e only green wood remains). It's a rather cost effective way to prevent forest fires, but has very little in common with the kind of raking we are better familiar with.
